{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:37:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22654"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22654","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22654"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0.08,0.29,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15601"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111352"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15601","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15601"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22654"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93482"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1094"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"4173"},{"type":"tags","id":"9339"},{"type":"tags","id":"9644"},{"type":"tags","id":"12922"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45204"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46341"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111352","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111352"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of intermittent difficulty swallowing solids. About once a week she coughs during meals with a brief choking sensation that settles spontaneously. She denies regurgitation, weight loss, chest pain, heartburn, food impaction, or odynophagia. Over the past month she has felt tired and lethargic. She eats a varied diet and has maintained her weight.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history is otherwise unremarkable. She reports heavy menstrual bleeding with regular 28-day cycles, bleeding lasting about seven days with passage of clots. She does not take any regular medications. She does not smoke and drinks alcohol occasionally. She works as a teacher and has not travelled recently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well. Her pulse rate is 76/min, blood pressure 122/74 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. There is no lymphadenopathy, no oral candidiasis, and the abdomen is soft and non-tender without organomegaly. There are no stigmata of chronic disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA contrast study is performed (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tun6FYBw7wpotvKdXkTPvDGFo0NyeQ.jpg\u0022\u003EImage 1\u003C/a\u003E, \u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cLYaVcZlbmFivO96FHNFVWBXWrAgqL.jpg\u0022\u003E2\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Pharyngeal pouch","Eosinophilic oesophagitis","Carcinoma of the oesophagus","Peptic stricture","Post-cricoid web"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe barium swallow study shows a thin, short, symmetric narrowing at the post-cricoid upper oesophagus with transient hold-up and contrast passing rapidly through on subsequent swallows.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntermittent solid-food dysphagia in a person with heavy menstrual bleeding and fatigue suggests iron deficiency contributing to an upper oesophageal web. Barium swallow features of a thin, symmetric, short narrowing at the post-cricoid region with rapid contrast transit are typical. Management includes confirming iron deficiency with iron studies, iron replacement, and consideration of endoscopic dilation if symptoms persist.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPost-cricoid web\u003C/strong\u003E is most consistent with the described barium findings and clinical context. Upper oesophageal webs are thin mucosal membranes in the post-cricoid region causing intermittent dysphagia, often associated with iron deficiency from heavy menstrual bleeding. The transient hold-up with rapid passage on repeat swallows supports a web rather than a fixed obstructing lesion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPharyngeal pouch\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with regurgitation of undigested food, halitosis, chronic cough, and occasionally a neck mass with gurgling on palpation. On contrast swallow it appears as a posterior outpouching above the upper oesophageal sphincter rather than a thin symmetric intraluminal narrowing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEosinophilic oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E commonly causes dysphagia and food bolus impaction in younger adults and is associated with atopy. Endoscopy or barium may show rings, furrows, or a small-calibre oesophagus, not a focal post-cricoid thin web. The absence of food impaction and the characteristic web appearance argues against this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECarcinoma of the oesophagus\u003C/strong\u003E usually presents with progressive dysphagia, weight loss, and sometimes odynophagia or chest pain. Imaging shows an irregular, shouldered, asymmetric stricture or an intraluminal mass. The patient\u2019s stable weight, intermittent symptoms, and a thin symmetric post-cricoid narrowing make malignancy unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic stricture\u003C/strong\u003E is a distal oesophageal complication of chronic reflux, producing progressive dysphagia to solids with a smooth concentric narrowing near the gastro-oesophageal junction. This patient denies reflux symptoms, and the lesion is located at the upper oesophagus, which is not typical for a peptic stricture.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Upper oesophageal webs can present with intermittent dysphagia to solids and are associated with iron deficiency from heavy menstrual bleeding.","Barium swallow typically shows a thin, symmetric narrowing at the post-cricoid region with transient hold-up and rapid transit of contrast.","Recognition of iron deficiency and web-related dysphagia should prompt iron studies, iron replacement, and consideration of endoscopic dilation if symptoms persist."],"references":["Patile M. Malipatel R, Devarbhavi H. Plummer\u2013Vinson syndrome: A decade\u2019s experience of 132 cases from a single center. J Gastroenterol Hepatol. 2021; 36:181-85.","Jacob D, Kearns C, Alhusseiny K, et al. Oesophageal web. Reference article, Radiopaedia.org (Accessed on 13 Aug 2025) https://doi.org/10.53347/rID-1750"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93482"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22654"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22022"},{"type":"media","id":"22023"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22022","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22022"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tun6FYBw7wpotvKdXkTPvDGFo0NyeQ.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/tun6FYBw7wpotvKdXkTPvDGFo0NyeQ.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":585,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"22023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22023"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cLYaVcZlbmFivO96FHNFVWBXWrAgqL.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/cLYaVcZlbmFivO96FHNFVWBXWrAgqL.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93482","links":{"self":"https://